1
00:00:04,086 --> 00:00:05,439
(Sponsors: The Ministry of Culture, Sports and Tourism...)

2
00:00:05,440 --> 00:00:06,950
(and Korea Creative Content Agency)

3
00:00:14,254 --> 00:00:16,684
(Day 3 in Antarctica)

4
00:00:20,254 --> 00:00:23,924
(Why is the crew gathered in the cafeteria?)

5
00:00:24,024 --> 00:00:26,464
Why did the secretary gather us here?

6
00:00:27,134 --> 00:00:28,394
Did we do something wrong?

7
00:00:29,294 --> 00:00:31,403
- There's word that...
- Were we too loud?

8
00:00:31,404 --> 00:00:33,604
- You've been snacking too much.
- We've been snacking too much.

9
00:00:34,634 --> 00:00:36,504
- We had too much of their coffee.
- Not me.

10
00:00:38,574 --> 00:00:40,204
(He's joking.)

11
00:00:41,544 --> 00:00:42,813
- Hey.
- Here he is.

12
00:00:42,814 --> 00:00:44,943
- I'm sorry for asking you here.
- We weren't busy.

13
00:00:44,944 --> 00:00:46,813
Why did you have us over on your break...

14
00:00:46,814 --> 00:00:48,113
- and not when you needed a hand?
- I had a request...

15
00:00:48,114 --> 00:00:50,324
and thought I'd bring it up during your break.

16
00:00:50,554 --> 00:00:53,424
A radio call just came in.

17
00:00:55,024 --> 00:00:59,023
You know the three from the Penguin Research Team.

18
00:00:59,024 --> 00:01:01,293
- The Penguin Research Team? Sure.
- Anyway,

19
00:01:01,294 --> 00:01:02,763
after being stuck inside for days,

20
00:01:02,764 --> 00:01:04,763
they're finally out at work...

21
00:01:04,764 --> 00:01:05,803
and completely swamped.

22
00:01:05,804 --> 00:01:08,274
- Due to bad weather, right?
- I'm afraid so.

23
00:01:08,334 --> 00:01:11,143
We were told that they couldn't make it to dinner today.

24
00:01:11,144 --> 00:01:13,144
- They can't make it back?
- That's right.

25
00:01:13,274 --> 00:01:15,944
That's why they requested a boxed meal.

26
00:01:16,984 --> 00:01:18,743
(A moment ago, the communication room)

27
00:01:18,744 --> 00:01:20,043
Communications,

28
00:01:20,044 --> 00:01:21,354
this is Kim Jee Hui from Summer Research Team.

29
00:01:22,214 --> 00:01:24,784
Our work out here has been extended,

30
00:01:25,154 --> 00:01:27,824
so we're requesting a boxed meal for dinner.

31
00:01:28,624 --> 00:01:31,694
Sure. We'll contact you after sorting out the details.

32
00:01:33,394 --> 00:01:34,663
Thank you.

33
00:01:34,664 --> 00:01:36,233
(The team is busy catching up on work...)

34
00:01:36,234 --> 00:01:37,803
(and has requested a boxed meal.)

35
00:01:37,804 --> 00:01:40,373
Since you're good at everything,

36
00:01:40,374 --> 00:01:43,673
I wanted to ask if that was possible.

37
00:01:43,674 --> 00:01:45,273
The Penguin Village...

38
00:01:45,274 --> 00:01:46,874
- must be far away.
- It is.

39
00:01:47,614 --> 00:01:50,113
- It's an hour away.
- Really?

40
00:01:50,114 --> 00:01:51,613
- An hour just to get there?
- At least 40 minutes.

41
00:01:51,614 --> 00:01:53,813
It takes two hours to get there and back.

42
00:01:53,814 --> 00:01:55,754
- Around an hour and a half.
- So for three meals... No way.

43
00:01:56,314 --> 00:01:59,124
Sometimes they have to work without eating anything.

44
00:01:59,154 --> 00:02:01,424
I've noticed them missing from the cafeteria.

45
00:02:02,854 --> 00:02:04,023
(King Sejong Station, Penguin Village)

46
00:02:04,024 --> 00:02:07,664
(Approximately 2km southeast of King Sejong Station)

47
00:02:09,334 --> 00:02:11,333
(Designated in 2009...)

48
00:02:11,334 --> 00:02:14,904
(as Korea's first Antarctic Specially Protected Area)

49
00:02:17,574 --> 00:02:23,113
(A key penguin habitat on King George Island)

50
00:02:23,114 --> 00:02:25,884
(A key penguin habitat on King George Island)

51
00:02:28,284 --> 00:02:34,024
(Penguin Village, Narebski Point)

52
00:02:46,734 --> 00:02:53,674
(The crew members who normally study the penguins here...)

53
00:02:54,844 --> 00:02:59,984
(walk 2km each way to enjoy warm meals.)

54
00:03:00,454 --> 00:03:04,554
(But if the weather's bad or they're busy working, )

55
00:03:05,184 --> 00:03:10,564
(they have boxed meals or occasionally skip eating.)

56
00:03:11,024 --> 00:03:12,293
How can we deliver the food to them?

57
00:03:12,294 --> 00:03:13,463
We need someone to guide us.

58
00:03:13,464 --> 00:03:15,233
Some members of my team...

59
00:03:15,234 --> 00:03:18,133
had work to do at Penguin Village but couldn't...

60
00:03:18,134 --> 00:03:20,934
- because of bad weather.
- How many are there?

61
00:03:21,034 --> 00:03:22,533
Two from my team.

62
00:03:22,534 --> 00:03:24,703
One researcher in biology and one in atmospheric science.

63
00:03:24,704 --> 00:03:28,544
Since they're going out there to continue their work,

64
00:03:28,574 --> 00:03:29,713
maybe you could make meals for them too.

65
00:03:29,714 --> 00:03:33,083
- They could take us there.
- Right.

66
00:03:33,084 --> 00:03:35,353
That's 3 for the penguin team, 2 for your team,

67
00:03:35,354 --> 00:03:37,953
and 4 for us, which is 9 in total.

68
00:03:37,954 --> 00:03:39,023
That's right.

69
00:03:39,024 --> 00:03:41,453
Chef An will have to cook...

70
00:03:41,454 --> 00:03:43,963
- for the others today.
- I guess so.

71
00:03:43,964 --> 00:03:47,094
The crew won't like it if we're not around.

72
00:03:47,194 --> 00:03:48,293
A boxed meal?

73
00:03:48,294 --> 00:03:50,633
- We'll discuss what we can cook.
- Sure.

74
00:03:50,634 --> 00:03:52,433
- Please give them a good meal.
- As if you need to ask.

75
00:03:52,434 --> 00:03:53,603
Thank you so much.

76
00:03:53,604 --> 00:03:54,904
We should work hard until our last day here.

77
00:03:55,604 --> 00:03:59,473
(Episode 3: Penguin Village, Antarctica City)

78
00:03:59,474 --> 00:04:00,873
What I heard...

79
00:04:00,874 --> 00:04:03,943
is that the penguin research team hates fish the most.

80
00:04:03,944 --> 00:04:05,983
- Any kind of fish.
- They don't want that at all.

81
00:04:05,984 --> 00:04:09,513
It smells strongly of fish where they work.

82
00:04:09,514 --> 00:04:12,253
Whatever we prepare shouldn't have any fishy smell.

83
00:04:12,254 --> 00:04:14,094
They really hate it.

84
00:04:14,724 --> 00:04:17,323
It should also taste good when cold.

85
00:04:17,324 --> 00:04:20,194
(Requirement for boxed meals 2: Must taste good when cold)

86
00:04:20,794 --> 00:04:22,634
How about a soup?

87
00:04:23,134 --> 00:04:24,733
- Maybe soup and rice.
- Will it go cold...

88
00:04:24,734 --> 00:04:26,303
if we prepare soup with rice?

89
00:04:26,304 --> 00:04:28,003
Wouldn't porridge be a better option?

90
00:04:28,004 --> 00:04:29,603
- Porridge?
- That's what I think.

91
00:04:29,604 --> 00:04:31,774
Porridge? I guess you have a point.

92
00:04:31,804 --> 00:04:34,473
Let's make a porridge with healthy ingredients then.

93
00:04:34,474 --> 00:04:36,913
- Like an energy booster.
- Sounds good.

94
00:04:36,914 --> 00:04:38,513
- I'd like that.
- Porridge is a nice idea.

95
00:04:38,514 --> 00:04:40,484
- I mean, it's cold outside.
- Right.

96
00:04:40,654 --> 00:04:41,683
From what I've heard,

97
00:04:41,684 --> 00:04:43,853
they usually pack cold rice balls...

98
00:04:43,854 --> 00:04:45,623
and eat them with ramyeon.

99
00:04:45,624 --> 00:04:47,084
That didn't sound right,

100
00:04:47,194 --> 00:04:49,024
especially since we're here...

101
00:04:49,054 --> 00:04:50,724
to cook for them.

102
00:04:52,224 --> 00:04:55,763
(All they want is for the Penguin Research Team...)

103
00:04:55,764 --> 00:04:59,234
(working out in the cold to have a hearty meal.)

104
00:04:59,434 --> 00:05:01,733
I'm fond of boxed meals myself,

105
00:05:01,734 --> 00:05:03,774
and I enjoy them.

106
00:05:04,244 --> 00:05:07,074
Being served a thoughtful boxed meal really boosts your energy.

107
00:05:07,814 --> 00:05:09,244
We should make porridge with meat.

108
00:05:09,514 --> 00:05:10,684
Porridge with meat.

109
00:05:11,284 --> 00:05:13,954
I also saw ugeoji and mallow in the pantry.

110
00:05:14,684 --> 00:05:17,624
I got it. Let's make mallow beef doenjang porridge.

111
00:05:17,954 --> 00:05:19,854
Doenjang porridge sounds amazing.

112
00:05:20,694 --> 00:05:21,793
That'd be delicious.

113
00:05:21,794 --> 00:05:23,194
Doenjang porridge sounds good.

114
00:05:23,624 --> 00:05:24,794
Nice.

115
00:05:27,764 --> 00:05:35,474
(Final decision: Mallow beef doenjang porridge)

116
00:05:39,074 --> 00:05:44,114
(Hang tight. We'll be right there with your tasty meal.)

117
00:05:45,484 --> 00:05:48,854
(They begin their kitchen prep after changing clothes.)

118
00:05:49,314 --> 00:05:50,384
Mallow.

119
00:05:51,024 --> 00:05:54,293
Just mallow won't give it enough texture.

120
00:05:54,294 --> 00:05:57,124
- Dried radish greens?
- Let's add dried radish greens too.

121
00:05:57,764 --> 00:06:00,664
(For a more interesting texture, )

122
00:06:00,794 --> 00:06:03,934
(they'll add dried radish greens to the mallow.)

123
00:06:04,004 --> 00:06:05,004
Frozen carrots.

124
00:06:05,005 --> 00:06:06,303
Frozen carrots?

125
00:06:06,304 --> 00:06:08,573
- Is one packet enough?
- Yes.

126
00:06:08,574 --> 00:06:10,133
Frozen carrots are over there.

127
00:06:10,134 --> 00:06:11,274
Onions.

128
00:06:11,304 --> 00:06:13,144
I only need a packet of onions.

129
00:06:15,614 --> 00:06:19,214
(Defrosting all the ingredients they need)

130
00:06:22,214 --> 00:06:23,684
(A chunk of meat)

131
00:06:28,394 --> 00:06:33,064
(Crew Paik's butchering show)

132
00:06:34,764 --> 00:06:39,304
(A thick cut of beef tenderloin)

133
00:06:41,734 --> 00:06:44,774
(It's cut into bite-sized cubes.)

134
00:06:45,274 --> 00:06:47,613
Oh, gosh. They don't have decent meat here,

135
00:06:47,614 --> 00:06:49,614
so I'm cooking porridge with beef tenderloin.

136
00:06:50,644 --> 00:06:52,143
(Normally, porridge is made with rump steak or chuck.)

137
00:06:52,144 --> 00:06:53,283
Does it smell?

138
00:06:53,284 --> 00:06:56,113
No, it's just that we usually cook steaks with tenderloin.

139
00:06:56,114 --> 00:06:58,623
I'm worried this might give off a gamey smell.

140
00:06:58,624 --> 00:07:00,454
(Today, they're making porridge with premium tenderloin.)

141
00:07:01,454 --> 00:07:03,254
What should we do if we're worried about the smell?

142
00:07:03,924 --> 00:07:05,693
Rinse and boil...

143
00:07:05,694 --> 00:07:07,463
the meat.

144
00:07:07,464 --> 00:07:09,163
- What about the red juice?
- You should rinse that out.

145
00:07:09,164 --> 00:07:10,904
Exactly, and that's most of the work.

146
00:07:11,564 --> 00:07:13,304
I'll cut the meat for you, so rinse it in water.

147
00:07:13,564 --> 00:07:14,634
Sure.

148
00:07:15,674 --> 00:07:17,744
- I'll rinse the rice in the pot.
- Sure.

149
00:07:18,874 --> 00:07:22,044
(Jong Hyeop's on rice duty.)

150
00:07:26,084 --> 00:07:29,414
(While Jong Hyeop calmly rinses the rice, )

151
00:07:29,554 --> 00:07:32,624
(Soo Hyang rinses the defrosted mallow and dried radish greens.)

152
00:07:33,184 --> 00:07:36,824
(Pressing down)

153
00:07:37,154 --> 00:07:40,934
(SUHO rinses the red juice off the meat.)

154
00:07:44,704 --> 00:07:48,404
(They prepare the ingredients like professionals.)

155
00:07:53,004 --> 00:07:56,144
(It's Crew Paik's turn now.)

156
00:07:57,744 --> 00:08:01,314
(Covering pot with oil)

157
00:08:02,814 --> 00:08:07,124
(A generous amount of sesame oil)

158
00:08:13,464 --> 00:08:15,893
(Crew Paik's Cooking Tip)

159
00:08:15,894 --> 00:08:18,403
(Stir-frying meat in sesame oil...)

160
00:08:18,404 --> 00:08:20,873
(adds flavor and removes odor.)

161
00:08:20,874 --> 00:08:23,204
Something already smells good.

162
00:08:23,974 --> 00:08:25,103
Amazing.

163
00:08:25,104 --> 00:08:27,044
(Once the meat is no longer red, add minced garlic.)

164
00:08:27,344 --> 00:08:28,414
Onions.

165
00:08:30,214 --> 00:08:31,284
Mushrooms.

166
00:08:33,984 --> 00:08:38,924
(The key ingredient of the porridge, doenjang)

167
00:08:39,824 --> 00:08:41,254
No, not that much.

168
00:08:48,464 --> 00:08:49,563
Awesome.

169
00:08:49,564 --> 00:08:51,634
Adding too much doenjang...

170
00:08:51,904 --> 00:08:54,104
can be off-putting for people who don't like it.

171
00:08:54,804 --> 00:08:56,874
Don't all Koreans like doenjang?

172
00:08:57,944 --> 00:09:00,474
(I guess you're right.)

173
00:09:00,974 --> 00:09:04,114
(While the porridge cooks, Soo Hyang and Jong Hyeop)

174
00:09:05,844 --> 00:09:09,214
(Slicing carrots)

175
00:09:13,984 --> 00:09:16,524
(Swoosh)

176
00:09:16,594 --> 00:09:17,994
You put in your own sound effect.

177
00:09:20,724 --> 00:09:22,764
(Swoosh)

178
00:09:24,564 --> 00:09:26,264
(Nice)

179
00:09:28,974 --> 00:09:30,133
It's like a risotto.

180
00:09:30,134 --> 00:09:31,243
(Adding rice to the thickened sauce)

181
00:09:31,244 --> 00:09:32,644
- Is it doenjang risotto?
- Yes, doenjang risotto.

182
00:09:33,374 --> 00:09:40,014
(Stirring well so that it doesn't stick)

183
00:09:40,784 --> 00:09:46,084
(Adjusting consistency with water)

184
00:09:47,594 --> 00:09:54,394
(Keep stirring until the rice is cooked!)

185
00:09:54,734 --> 00:09:58,104
(Shall we begin?)

186
00:09:59,834 --> 00:10:01,973
The key to good porridge is love...

187
00:10:01,974 --> 00:10:03,933
and steady effort.

188
00:10:03,934 --> 00:10:05,644
(Stirring for 15 minutes)

189
00:10:07,544 --> 00:10:10,844
(Sighing...)

190
00:10:11,284 --> 00:10:14,814
(After the pickled radish nightmare, )

191
00:10:15,584 --> 00:10:19,384
(he's now in a porridge nightmare.)

192
00:10:19,524 --> 00:10:21,253
I bet you're tired. Should I take over?

193
00:10:21,254 --> 00:10:23,294
(No, I'm good.)

194
00:10:23,394 --> 00:10:24,494
You...

195
00:10:24,624 --> 00:10:26,264
You remind me of Cinderella.

196
00:10:27,734 --> 00:10:28,994
Remy from "Ratatouille?"

197
00:10:29,364 --> 00:10:31,134
No, Cinderella.

198
00:10:32,104 --> 00:10:33,863
(SUHO-ella)

199
00:10:33,864 --> 00:10:36,034
You're like Cinderella, who had to do all the work.

200
00:10:36,734 --> 00:10:38,044
- Should I keep stirring?
- Yes.

201
00:10:40,044 --> 00:10:42,444
It would stick to the pan if I paused even for a moment,

202
00:10:42,944 --> 00:10:44,814
so I kept stirring.

203
00:10:47,554 --> 00:10:48,853
This is exhausting.

204
00:10:48,854 --> 00:10:52,684
(SUHO-ella stirred for 15 minutes more...)

205
00:10:53,084 --> 00:10:54,253
- Is it done?
- It is.

206
00:10:54,254 --> 00:10:55,293
Then, turn it on.

207
00:10:55,294 --> 00:10:56,494
(It's now time for the final step.)

208
00:10:56,954 --> 00:10:57,963
(Mallow and dried radish greens)

209
00:10:57,964 --> 00:10:59,094
In they go.

210
00:11:00,024 --> 00:11:01,064
Add them all.

211
00:11:01,164 --> 00:11:03,194
This looks delicious.

212
00:11:03,994 --> 00:11:05,164
Look at that.

213
00:11:06,050 --> 00:11:06,859
Goodness.

214
00:11:07,334 --> 00:11:09,434
(Pouring it all in)

215
00:11:09,934 --> 00:11:12,344
Let me give you a reason to stay motivated.

216
00:11:16,644 --> 00:11:17,884
Oh, my.

217
00:11:18,014 --> 00:11:19,344
Delicious, right?

218
00:11:20,744 --> 00:11:21,913
The mushrooms smell great.

219
00:11:21,914 --> 00:11:26,954
(The aroma of mushrooms fills the mouth.)

220
00:11:27,054 --> 00:11:29,154
- Are you motivated?
- I am.

221
00:11:29,424 --> 00:11:33,294
(I just need to stir a bit more, and it'll be done!)

222
00:11:34,364 --> 00:11:36,734
(Looking around)

223
00:11:38,434 --> 00:11:39,733
Should we just season some salt-pickled radish?

224
00:11:39,734 --> 00:11:40,974
Do we need more side dishes?

225
00:11:41,004 --> 00:11:42,434
- Side dishes?
- Yes.

226
00:11:43,434 --> 00:11:47,044
We have some salt-pickled radish left over from a previous serving.

227
00:11:47,144 --> 00:11:48,273
Let's pack this as a side dish.

228
00:11:48,274 --> 00:11:50,044
(Let's pack this too.)

229
00:11:51,214 --> 00:11:53,844
(How does it taste?)

230
00:11:54,044 --> 00:11:57,924
(The first bite goes to the hard-working Cinderella.)

231
00:11:58,624 --> 00:11:59,724
How is it?

232
00:11:59,884 --> 00:12:01,254
- Wait.
- I gave you one slice.

233
00:12:01,654 --> 00:12:02,794
Hold on.

234
00:12:03,254 --> 00:12:05,294
To be honest, this is really salty.

235
00:12:05,594 --> 00:12:06,993
What was that?

236
00:12:06,994 --> 00:12:08,364
(What?)

237
00:12:08,734 --> 00:12:09,863
Can you taste this for me?

238
00:12:09,864 --> 00:12:10,933
(What does the seasoning checker think?)

239
00:12:10,934 --> 00:12:12,034
How is it?

240
00:12:13,464 --> 00:12:15,003
- It's salty.
- Is it?

241
00:12:15,004 --> 00:12:17,333
(It's salty.)

242
00:12:17,334 --> 00:12:18,574
It's close to just pickled radish.

243
00:12:18,844 --> 00:12:20,243
- What?
- It's close to just pickled radish.

244
00:12:20,244 --> 00:12:21,414
She's right.

245
00:12:22,614 --> 00:12:23,743
Really?

246
00:12:23,744 --> 00:12:25,344
(Then, I have a way!)

247
00:12:25,744 --> 00:12:26,843
(It's time to present Paik Jong Won's magic.)

248
00:12:26,844 --> 00:12:28,053
Sugar.

249
00:12:28,054 --> 00:12:29,714
(It's time to present Paik Jong Won's magic.)

250
00:12:30,784 --> 00:12:33,324
(Sesame seeds)

251
00:12:33,654 --> 00:12:36,124
(Sugar)

252
00:12:36,494 --> 00:12:38,764
(Sesame oil to enhance the nutty flavor)

253
00:12:39,194 --> 00:12:40,894
(Adding spice with chili powder)

254
00:12:42,034 --> 00:12:43,064
Nice.

255
00:12:43,364 --> 00:12:47,004
I think this will go well with doenjang porridge.

256
00:12:47,674 --> 00:12:49,733
This looks delicious.

257
00:12:49,734 --> 00:12:51,874
(Did it revive the salt-pickled radish?)

258
00:12:52,604 --> 00:12:53,804
Is the seasoning right?

259
00:12:59,044 --> 00:13:01,714
